description.value: Two fragments of an ostracon from a pottery vessel that were originally glued together. Traces of the glue covered part of the text.  Three lines of hieratic written in black ink. The first is written in a neat and small hand writing. Underneath a two signs of a larger and clearly different hand writing, followed by a much smaller signs. The third line is written in tall signs again like the beginning of the second line.  The vessel is made of marl or imported clay, probably an amphora, wheel made. On the inside remains of a brown substance that could be related to the gluing though its different to the glue between the two sherd. Bits of clay are stuck onto to the inside from the production of the vessel.

legal.credit_line: © The Trustees of the British Museum

description.value: Fragment of an ostracon from a pottery vessel, showing two lines of hieratic text written in black ink. The sherd is part of the handle and the body, with the lower part of the handle remaining. There is a black horizontal line at the base of the handle. The text seems to be turned by 180° in relation to the orientation of the vessel, meaning that the text was added after the breakage of the vessel.  The vessel is made of Nile clay, with a whitish self-slip and belonged originally to an amphora.

description.value: Ostracon that originates from the upper part of a pottery jar, made of a Nile B2 fabric, red slip on the surface. The sherd was cut into a rectangular shape, broken off at the right side. There are five lines of hieratic text written in black ink with the beginning of the teaching of Amenemhat on it, a lot of the text to the right is lost now.  1) [...] sA-R' ('Imn-m-HA.t)| 2) [...] Dd=f x' m-nTr sDm n- 3) [...] .kw m-HAw Hr- 4) (I5 as Determinative) 5) [...tmmt] khprw  1) [Beginning of the Teaching / made by the Majesty of the Dual King, Sehotepibre], / the Son of Ra Amenemhat, 2) [the justified, / when he spoke in a revelation / to his son, the Lord of All]. / He said, 'Rise as a god! / Listen to  3) [what I tell you, / that you may be king of the land, and rule the Banks, / increas]ing the 4) 5) [good. / Concentrate against subjects who prove non]-existent.

description.value: Ostracon that originates from the upper part of a pottery jar, made of a Nile B2 fabric, red slip on the surface. The sherd was cut into a rectangular shape, broken off at the right side. There are five lines of hieratic text written in black ink with the beginning of the teaching of Amenemhat on it, a lot of the text to the right is lost now.  1) [...] sA-R' ('Imn-m-HA.t)| 2) [...] Dd=f x' m-nTr sDm n- 3) [...] .kw m-HAw Hr- 4) (I5 as Determinative) 5) [...tmmt] khprw  1) [Beginning of the Teaching / made by the Majesty of the Dual King, Sehotepibre], / the Son of Ra Amenemhat, 2) [the justified, / when he spoke in a revelation / to his son, the Lord of All]. / He said, 'Rise as a god! / Listen to  3) [what I tell you, / that you may be king of the land, and rule the Banks, / increas]ing the 4) 5) [good. / Concentrate against subjects who prove non]-existent.
